m\n*[[IAI Ghost]], rotary mini UAV\n\n==Science==\n===Biology===\n*[[Ghost cell]], enlarged eosinophilic epithelial cell with eosinophilic cytoplasm but without a nucleus\n*[[Ghost lineage]], an inferred phylogenetic lineage\n*[[Ghost population]], an inferred statistical population\n\n===Physics===\n*[[Ghost (physics)]], unphysical state in quantum field theory\n**[[Faddeev\u2013Popov ghost]]s, extraneous fields introduced into gauge quantum field theories to maintain the consistency of the path integral formulation\n\n==Other uses==\n*[[Ghost (fashion brand)]]\n*[[Ghost (mascot)]], a joke mainly used by sports fans in Latin America\n*[[Global horizontal sounding technique]], an atmospheric field research project in the late 1960s\n*[[Juliet Marine Systems Ghost]], watercraft\n*[[Rolls-Royce Ghost]], car\n\n==See also==\n*[[Apparition (disambiguation)]]\n*[[GH057ayame]] (born 1988), gamertag of Eric Hewitt, professional ''Halo'' player\n*[[Ghost in the machine (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ghost Island (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ghost pepper]] (''Bhut jolokia'')\n*[[Ghost town (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ghost train (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ghosted (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ghosting (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Haunted house]]\n*[[Phantom (disambiguation)|Phantom]]\n*{{Look from|Ghost}}\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Mburrell", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghost_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Colorado's 1st Senate district", "text_new": "{{Short description|American legislative district}}\n{{Infobox legislative district\n|state=Colorado\n|district=1\n|chamber=Senate\n|image=[[File:Colorado Senate District 1 (2010).png|350px]]\n|representative=[[Jerry Sonnenberg]]\n|party=Republican\n|residence=Sterling\n|Democratic=13.6\n|Republican=50.5\n|NPP=34.5\n|percent_white=74\n|percent_black=2\n|percent_hispanic=21\n|percent_asian=1\n|percent_native_american=\n|percent_pacific_islander=\n|percent_other_race=2\n|percent_remainder_of_multiracial=\n|population=148,526<ref name=\"Census\">{{Cite web|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/61000US08001-state-senate-district-1-co/|title=State Senate District 1, CO|publisher=Census Reporter|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reg\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/VoterRegNumbers/2020/March/VotersBySenateDist.pdf|title=Total Registered Voters by State Senate District, Party, and Status|website=|publisher=Colorado Secretary of State|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|population_year=2018\n|voting_age=\n|citizen_voting_age=\n|registered=103,238\n|notes=\n}}\n'''[[Colorado]]'s 1st Senate district''' is one of 35 districts in the [[Colorado Senate]]. It has been represented by [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Jerry Sonnenberg]] since 2015, succeeding fellow Republican [[Greg Brophy]].<ref name=\"CO Site\">{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/jerry-sonnenberg|title=Senator Jerry Sonnenberg |publisher=Colorado General Assembly|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nDistrict 1 covers much of the [[Eastern Plains]] in the state's northeastern corner, including all of [[Cheyenne County, Colorado|Cheyenne]], [[Elbert County, Colorado|Elbert]], [[Kit Carson County, Colorado|Kit Carson]], [[Lincoln County, Colorado|Lincoln]], [[Logan County, Colorado|Logan]], [[Morgan County, Colorado|Morgan]], [[Phillips County, Colorado|Phillips]], [[Sedgwick County, Colorado|Sedgwick]], [[Washington County, Colorado|Washington]], and [[Yuma County, Colorado|Yuma Counties]] and parts of [[Weld County, Colorado|Weld County]]. Communities in the district include [[Julesburg, Colorado|Julesburg]], [[Holyoke, Colorado|Holyoke]], [[Sterling, Colorado|Sterling]], [[Brush, Colorado|Brush]], [[Fort Morgan, Colorado|Fort Morgan]], [[Eaton, Colorado|Eaton]], [[Kersey, Colorado|Kersey]], [[Lochbuie, Colorado|Lochbuie]], [[Hudson, Colorado|Hudson]], [[Keenesburg, Colorado|Keenesburg]], [[Ault, Colorado|Ault]], [[Akron, Colorado|Akron]], [[Wray, Colorado|Wray]], [[Yuma, Colorado|Yuma]], [[Burlington, Colorado|Burlington]], [[Limon, Colorado|Limon]], [[Elizabeth, Colorado|Elizabeth]], [[Ponderosa Park, Colorado|Ponderosa Park]], and [[Cheyenne Wells, Colorado|Cheyenne Wells]].<ref name=\"CO Site\"/><ref name=\"Reg\"/>\n\nThe district is located entirely within [[Colorado's 4th congressional district]], and overlaps with the 48th, 63rd, 64th, and 65th districts of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2019/7/30/1848730/-How-do-counties-House-districts-and-legislative-districts-all-overlap-These-new-tools-show-you|author=David Jarman|title=How do counties, House districts, and legislative districts all overlap?|publisher=Daily Kos|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> It borders the states of [[Wyoming]], [[Nebraska]], and [[Kansas]].<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n\n==Recent election results==\nColorado Senators are elected to staggered four-year terms; under normal circumstances, the 1st district holds elections in midterm years.\n===2018===\n{{Election box begin no change| title= [[2018 Colorado State Senate election]], District 1<ref name=\"Ballotpedia\">{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_District_1|title=Colorado State Senate District 1|publisher=Ballotpedia|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n